SLUG: art-print-storefront

# Startup brief: Art Print Storefront (Vibe / Claude Coding Tutor)

Note on slugs: run artifacts for this job live in the existing run directory
`upwork-runs/let-s-create-this-shopify/` (already created by the graph). The
PUBLIC-FACING demo slug that the demo-builder must use everywhere it matters is
`art-print-storefront`: the demo folder
`../michaelwegter.com/public/demos/art-print-storefront/`, the `slug` field in
`src/data/workSamples.js`, and the live route
`/work-samples/art-print-storefront`. Use `art-print-storefront` for anything a
visitor or URL sees; keep run-time intermediates in the existing run dir.

## What the client actually wants
The client is a fine-art photographer building a minimal, editorial, gallery-
forward Shopify storefront to sell photography prints (horizontal scroll gallery,
print product pages with size/edition variants, clean checkout). The deeper ask is
NOT "build it for me." It is tutoring: a patient, screen-share "vibe coding" tutor
who builds alongside them in real time using Claude, explains the why behind each
decision, and teaches them to prompt Claude well so they can maintain and extend
the theme themselves. Winning this is about demonstrating both real Shopify/OS 2.0
craft AND the ability to coach a non-developer through AI-assisted development.

## Recommended demo direction
Build a working, gallery-forward art-print storefront demo that doubles as a
teaching artifact. The single most impressive thing to show: a smooth horizontal
scrolling gallery with drag + arrow navigation on the homepage, leading into a
print product page with a size/edition variant selector and live price update,
then "add to cart" into a mock cart and a mock checkout. Back it with a real
mw-backend blueprint providing mock login (JWT, mirror the existing auth pattern)
and a mock checkout/order endpoint, seeded with prints whose imagery comes from a
free-to-use source (Unsplash/Pexels/Picsum or curated public-domain art). Frame
the front end as OS 2.0 "sections and blocks" thinking even though the demo is a
static same-origin app, so the client sees the exact architecture they will build
in Liquid. The hero is the gallery + variant-to-cart flow; the login + mock
checkout proves the "real backend" Michael asked for. A short, embedded "How I'd
coach this with Claude" panel (the prompt I'd write, what to review, what to catch)
turns the demo into proof of the tutoring value, which is the actual job.

## Demo direction matches Michael's explicit notes
- Real backend in mw-backend: add an `art_store_blueprint.py` (clone the
  `spotify_blueprint.py` structure) with mock login + mock checkout. Do NOT touch
  auth core, DB schema, or existing blueprints beyond registering the blueprint.
- Login + mock checkout: required. JWT mock auth like the existing pattern; a
  checkout endpoint that returns a fake confirmed order. No real payments.
- Images from a free-to-use site: source prints from a free/royalty-free provider
  and record the exact source + license in research.md so the deck can cite it.

## Constraints, risks, red flags to respect
- This is the tutor's portfolio proof, not a production Shopify theme. Lean full
  per CLAUDE.md, but do not try to run an actual Shopify dev store. The demo is a
  same-origin static front end + mw-backend, presented as "the architecture we'll
  recreate in Liquid/OS 2.0."
- US-only applicants: Michael qualifies; have the cover letter note US-based.
- Scope creep risk: keep to 1 hero (gallery + variant-to-cart) + at most 2
  supporting features (mock login, mock checkout). Five marketing pages are NOT
  all required in the demo; show the hero flow well, not every page.
- Performance + "minimal dependencies" is a stated value: prefer vanilla JS / a
  CDN-light build so the demo itself models the "fast load" principle.
- Voice/positioning: the proposal must foreground tutoring and communication, not
  just delivery. Include that Michael uses Claude, Codex, and GitHub Copilot daily
  in his full-time job and freelancing, can communicate well, and can coach the
  client to "Claude code" the site themselves.

## Quality + naming guidance for downstream
- intake: Extract EVERY explicit requirement precisely and verbatim-ish into
  brief.json as a checklist: all 5 required pages; all 6 key features (OS 2.0
  sections+blocks, custom Liquid horizontal gallery, variant-based size/edition,
  metafields for edition numbering/print details, responsive mobile, fast load /
  minimal deps); the session-style asks (screen-share build-along, explain the
  why, craft/iterate Claude prompts, written summaries/checklists); and the ideal-
  candidate signals (OS 2.0 Liquid, comfort with AI tools, tutoring non-devs,
  plain-language explanation, Shopify portfolio). Capture Michael's notes as
  explicit requirements too: real mw-backend, mock login, mock checkout, free-use
  images, tutor/communication framing, daily Claude/Codex/Copilot experience.
  Flag US-only as a gating constraint.
- planner: Choose hero = horizontal gallery + variant-to-cart; supporting = mock
  login and mock checkout. Greenlight the mw-backend blueprint explicitly (Michael
  asked for a real backend). Record the lean-full decision.
- demo-builder: Use slug `art-print-storefront` for the public demo folder,
  workSamples `slug`, and route. Add `art_store_blueprint.py` by cloning
  `spotify_blueprint.py`; register in `server.py`; keep CORS open.

